\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 # Founder Update: Reimagining the First-Time Citizen Experience\
\
During product review, an important realization emerged:\
\
The Local Government page is no longer the beginning of the experience.\
\
It is the destination.\
\
The current Local Government page successfully presents the constitutional profile of a community once the citizen has arrived there. However, it assumes the citizen already knows where they are going. For most users, this is unlikely to be true.\
\
Most Nigerians will not open the application because they want to look up their Local Government Chairman.\
\
They will open it because they are curious, because they have heard about the platform, or because they want to understand their place within Nigeria.\
\
The onboarding experience should therefore become an act of discovery rather than navigation.\
\
---\
\
# New Product Direction\
\
The application should begin with Nigeria itself.\
\
Not with a dashboard.\
\
Not with a search field.\
\
Not with a Local Government profile.\
\
The first screen should be intentionally minimal and almost cinematic.\
\
The citizen should immediately understand:\
\
"I am about to explore Nigeria."\
\
This establishes the emotional tone before introducing any constitutional information.\
\
---\
\
# The Opening Experience\
\
The first screen should contain only a few elements.\
\
\'95 A beautiful, simplified, interactive map or globe-like representation of Nigeria.\
\
\'95 A calm, subtle animation.\
\
\'95 Minimal interface chrome.\
\
\'95 One clear question.\
\
For example:\
\
> You know your President.\
>\
> You know your Governor.\
>\
> But do you know your Local Government Chairman?\
\
This should not feel like onboarding.\
\
It should feel like curiosity.\
\
The objective is not to explain the application.\
\
The objective is to encourage exploration.\
\
---\
\
# Nigeria as the Entry Point\
\
Nigeria should become the application's first constitutional object.\
\
Rather than immediately displaying thousands of pieces of information, the interface introduces the country's constitutional geography through interaction.\
\
The map should not resemble Google Maps or GIS software.\
\
Instead it should be stylised and simplified.\
\
The interaction should prioritise clarity and delight over geographic precision.\
\
The citizen should immediately feel invited to touch the country.\
\
---\
\
# Interactive State Exploration\
\
The states should surround the national map in a dynamic but restrained manner.\
\
The user should be able to:\
\
\'95 Swipe left or right to rotate around Nigeria.\
\
\'95 Tap directly on any state.\
\
\'95 Select a state from a dropdown.\
\
All three interactions should drive exactly the same underlying state.\
\
There must never be separate interaction paths.\
\
If the user selects a state from the dropdown, the animated map should react exactly as though the user tapped the state.\
\
The selected state should smoothly move into focus.\
\
The rest of Nigeria gently fades into the background.\
\
The application should never instantly jump.\
\
It should animate.\
\
The citizen should feel that they are physically moving through the constitutional geography of the country.\
\
---\
\
# Progressive Information Disclosure\
\
One important principle:\
\
Never overwhelm the citizen.\
\
When a state becomes active, only one layer of information should appear.\
\
Examples:\
\
\'95 State name\
\
\'95 Governor\
\
\'95 Number of Local Governments\
\
\'95 Population\
\
\'95 Capital\
\
Not every piece of information should appear simultaneously.\
\
Everything should gently fade into view as part of the interaction.\
\
The application should always reveal information progressively.\
\
This creates curiosity while keeping the interface extremely clean.\
\
---\
\
# Selecting a Local Government\
\
Once a state is selected, the Local Governments belonging to that state become available.\
\
The citizen should then be able to:\
\
\'95 Tap a Local Government directly.\
\
\'95 Select one from a dropdown.\
\
Again, these should be two views of exactly the same state.\
\
Selecting from the dropdown should animate the map exactly as if the Local Government itself had been tapped.\
\
No separate interaction models should exist.\
\
---\
\
# Transition Into the Constitutional Profile\
\
Once a Local Government has been selected, the application performs a final transition into the already-designed Local Government profile.\
\
The current profile design remains unchanged.\
\
The onboarding experience simply becomes the journey that leads into it.\
\
The Local Government page is now understood as the destination of discovery rather than the application's home screen.\
\
---\
\
# Location Awareness\
\
Location services should enhance the experience without becoming mandatory.\
\
On first launch:\
\
If location permission is granted:\
\
The application should identify the user's state.\
\
Example:\
\
"Looks like you're in Oyo State."\
\
The corresponding state should already be centred within the animated map.\
\
The citizen remains free to choose another state.\
\
Nothing is forced.\
\
If location is unavailable:\
\
The experience simply begins centred on Nigeria.\
\
No functionality is lost.\
\
---\
\
# Returning Users\
\
The exploration experience primarily exists for first-time users.\
\
Once a citizen chooses a Local Government, that Local Government becomes their Home.\
\
Subsequent launches should open directly into the Local Government profile.\
\
The onboarding experience should always remain accessible through Explore, allowing citizens to discover other states and Local Governments whenever they wish.\
\
---\
\
# Design Principles\
\
The new onboarding should embody several principles:\
\
## 1. Discovery over Navigation\
\
Citizens should feel they are exploring Nigeria rather than filling out a form.\
\
---\
\
## 2. Progressive Disclosure\
\
Only one idea should be presented at a time.\
\
Information should appear gradually through animation.\
\
---\
\
## 3. Shared Interaction Model\
\
Touch interaction and dropdown selection must always remain synchronised.\
\
Every input method should produce the same visual response.\
\
---\
\
## 4. Motion with Meaning\
\
Animations should communicate constitutional geography.\
\
Transitions should reinforce understanding of the country's structure rather than simply decorate the interface.\
\
---\
\
## 5. Calm by Default\
\
The interface should remain spacious, quiet and intentionally restrained.\
\
The objective is confidence rather than excitement.\
\
---\
\
# Product Vision\
\
The application should no longer feel like a database or government directory.\
\
It should feel like entering Nigeria through a living constitutional map.\
\
The citizen discovers:\
\
Nigeria\
\
\uc0\u8595 \
\
Their State\
\
\uc0\u8595 \
\
Their Local Government\
\
\uc0\u8595 \
\
Their constitutional community\
\
Only after this journey do they arrive at the Local Government profile.\
\
The onboarding experience therefore becomes an introduction to both the country and the constitutional structure that CAOS understands.\
\
The first experience is no longer:\
\
"Find your Local Government."\
\
It becomes:\
\
"Discover where you belong."\
\
\
\
