# Founder Constitutional Update\
## Citizen Application v1 \'97 The First Native Application of the CAOS Operating System\
\
**Status:** Founder Ratified\
**Type:** Constitutional Product Direction\
**Scope:** Citizen Application (v1)\
**Date:** July 2026\
\
---\
\
# Executive Summary\
\
The Citizen application has now been constitutionally reframed.\
\
It is no longer a demonstration application ("Who is my Local Government Chairman?").\
\
It is no longer a vertical slice.\
\
It is the **first native application built on top of the CAOS Operating System**.\
\
Its purpose is not to expose one claim.\
\
Its purpose is to expose the constitutional state of a Nigerian community.\
\
This marks an important milestone in CAOS' evolution.\
\
Until now, the operating system has been focused on producing constitutional truth.\
\
The Citizen application is the first product focused on allowing citizens to experience constitutional truth.\
\
---\
\
# Core Design Principle\
\
The application is built around a single constitutional abstraction:\
\
> Every Local Government Area has one constitutional profile.\
\
That profile is rendered from constitutional truth.\
\
The page itself never changes.\
\
Only the constitutional state changes.\
\
This principle becomes one of the foundational UI principles of CAOS.\
\
---\
\
# Constitutional Rendering Model\
\
Every Local Government page is produced from:\
\
Local Government Object\
\
+\
\
Relationships\
\
+\
\
Truth Products\
\
+\
\
Projection Rules\
\
\uc0\u8595 \
\
Citizen UI\
\
No page-specific logic should exist.\
\
No hardcoded Local Government layouts should exist.\
\
The application contains one Local Government template.\
\
The operating system projects constitutional truth into that template.\
\
---\
\
# Why the Local Government?\
\
The Local Government has been adopted as the primary citizen anchor.\
\
Reasons:\
\
\'95 Every citizen belongs to one Local Government.\
\
\'95 Every elected representative ultimately relates to a Local Government.\
\
\'95 Budgets are ultimately spent somewhere.\
\
\'95 Projects ultimately exist somewhere.\
\
\'95 Public institutions ultimately serve somewhere.\
\
\'95 Elections ultimately terminate somewhere.\
\
The Local Government therefore becomes the constitutional home of the citizen.\
\
The application is not centred around politicians.\
\
It is centred around place.\
\
---\
\
# Page Identity\
\
Every Local Government page begins with the identity of the place.\
\
Identity consists of:\
\
\'95 Header Image\
\
\'95 Official Logo\
\
\'95 Local Government Name\
\
\'95 State\
\
\'95 Quick Information\
\
Identity should remain visually dominant.\
\
The user should immediately feel:\
\
"I am inside Ibadan North."\
\
rather than\
\
"I am viewing Chairman X."\
\
---\
\
# Header Image Rules\
\
Every Local Government should have a unique visual identity.\
\
Priority order:\
\
1. Official or high-quality photograph representing the Local Government.\
\
2. Representative landscape or landmark photograph.\
\
3. State-level photograph.\
\
4. State-level artistic illustration.\
\
5. CAOS placeholder artwork.\
\
Every page should always feel visually complete.\
\
The absence of an LGA-specific image should never produce an empty experience.\
\
---\
\
# Logo Rules\
\
Priority order:\
\
1. Official Local Government logo (if available).\
\
2. Official State Government logo.\
\
No custom CAOS logos should replace official government identity.\
\
CAOS remains intentionally invisible within the page.\
\
---\
\
# Local Government Name\
\
The Local Government name is the primary visual element.\
\
Examples:\
\
Ibadan North\
\
Gwagwalada\
\
Lagos Island\
\
Nsukka\
\
The page is fundamentally about the place.\
\
Not the office holders.\
\
---\
\
